  <sec id="sec-SciMod">
    <title>A scientific model for the DCJ procedure</title>
    <p>A <italic>scientific (causal) model</italic> describe the causal
    assumptions and mechanisms underlying a system, and facilitate
    inferences about causal relationships from data
    (<xref alt="Hitchcock 2023" rid="ref-Hitchcock_2023" ref-type="bibr">Hitchcock
    2023</xref>).</p>
    <p>To aid in the translation and visualization of the assumption
    underlying the DCJ procedure, Directed Acyclic Graphs (DAG) and
    Structural Causal Models (SCM)
    (<xref alt="Pearl 2009" rid="ref-Pearl_2009" ref-type="bibr">Pearl
    2009</xref>;
    <xref alt="Pearl, Glymour, and Jewell 2016" rid="ref-Pearl_et_al_2016" ref-type="bibr">Pearl,
    Glymour, and Jewell 2016</xref>;
    <xref alt="Cinelli, Forney, and Pearl 2022" rid="ref-Cinelli_et_al_2021" ref-type="bibr">Cinelli,
    Forney, and Pearl 2022</xref>) are employed. DAG are
    <styled-content style="color:red;">(…)</styled-content>. While SCM
    are <styled-content style="color:red;">(…)</styled-content>.</p>
    <fig id="fig-IEflowchart">
      <caption><p>Figure 2: Scientific model for the DCJ
      method</p></caption>
